1. Instructions - Start Here!.Contractor - Covid-19 Vaccine Mandate Co:
Overview: On August 30, 2021, the Colorado Department of Public Health & Environment, pursuant to  its emergency rule making authority, issued regulations under Standards for Hospital and Health Facilities at 6 CCR 1011-1 Chapter 2, Part 12 (the “Emergency Standards”).  The Emergency Standards require all Centura contractors working in Hospitals and Health Facilities to have their first dose of the COVID-19 vaccination no later than September 30, 2021, and the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccination no later than October 31, 2021. Therefore, Centura will be required to comply with this Emergency standards. The Emergency Standards require that each licensed entity report the number of vaccinated contractors to the state or those with exemptions. 

In order for Centura to show compliance to this Emergency Standard, we need you to provide the information required on the "Vendor Compliance Form" sheet in this workbook.  This data must include the entire population at the time of submission.  This data is NOT incremental to your last submission.
If you need any help with this MS Excel Template please send questions to:

Glossary.Field: Number of Employees that have complete vaccine series and are eligible for booster
Glossary.Intructions:
Please enter the total number of employees that have completed the vaccine series are are currently eligible for the booster

Currently, CDC is recommending that moderately to severely immunocompromised people receive an additional dose. This includes people who have:
-Been receiving active cancer treatment for tumors or cancers of the blood
-Received an organ transplant and are taking medicine to suppress the immune system
-Received a stem cell transplant within the last 2 years or are taking medicine to suppress the immune system
-Moderate or severe primary immunodeficiency (such as DiGeorge syndrome, Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome)
-Advanced or untreated HIV infection
-Active treatment with high-dose corticosteroids or other drugs that may suppress your immune response
People should talk to their healthcare provider about their medical condition, and whether getting an additional dose is appropriate for them.
